    <segment id="1" parent="19" relname="span">
Intuitiveness has been found to quite different than analysis.</segment>
    <segment id="2" parent="1" relname="evidence">  I have found myself 
learning new applications by clicking on icons without analyzing what it represents.</segment>
    <segment id="3" parent="20" relname="span">  In 
other words, it intuitive is familiarly.</segment>
    <segment id="4" parent="10" relname="sequence"> For example, the first time we worked with MS 
Word, the disk icon was unfamiliar to us.</segment>
    <segment id="5" parent="16" relname="span">  Now, in every application, we intuitively know 
what the disk icon represents</segment>
    <segment id="11" parent="5" relname="volitional-cause"> because we are familiar with it.</segment>
    <segment id="6" parent="12" relname="volitional-cause">  When you have worked 
with an application for a long a time,</segment>
    <segment id="12" parent="18" relname="span"> you tend to forget the basics.</segment>
    <segment id="7" parent="23" relname="span">  

In a study by Raskin, he summarized that intuitiveness should be replaced with 
familiarity</segment>
    <segment id="13" parent="7" relname="volitional-cause"> because users are more familiar with UI or peripheral.</segment>
    <segment id="8" parent="14" relname="means">  By increasing our 
use with it,</segment>
    <segment id="14" parent="21" relname="span"> we begin to increase our experience</segment>
    <segment id="15" parent="22" relname="span"> where we can now say that it is intuitive.</segment>
    <segment id="9" parent="26" relname="elaboration">
Every UI, with increase usage, will eventually become intuitively.  
</segment>
